{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621794"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:58:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16773"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16773","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16773"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0,0.02,0.94]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9464"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9464"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16773"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52344"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5065"},{"type":"tags","id":"5066"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"8486"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22362"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ELoop diuretics are commonly prescribed medications for managing fluid overload in heart failure and other oedematous states.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of loop diuretics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks sodium channels in the collecting duct","Inhibits carbonic anhydrase in the proximal tubule","Antagonises aldosterone receptors in the distal tubule","Blocks aquaporin channels throughout the nephron","Inhibits the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the thick ascending limb"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELoop diuretics primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the thick ascending limb\u003C/strong\u003E of the loop of Henle. This prevents the reabsorption of these ions, leading to increased urinary excretion of sodium, potassium, and chloride. The resulting loss of the medullary concentration gradient also reduces water reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking sodium channels in the collecting duct\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of amiloride, a potassium-sparing diuretic. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting carbonic anhydrase in the proximal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E describes how acetazolamide works to reduce bicarbonate reabsorption. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonising aldosterone receptors in the distal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E represents the mechanism of spironolactone, which prevents sodium retention and potassium excretion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking aquaporin channels throughout the nephron\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism employed by any current diuretic medication, though aquaporins are important for water reabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe potent diuretic effect of these medications makes them particularly useful in conditions where rapid reduction of fluid overload is needed, such as acute pulmonary oedema or severe peripheral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Loop diuretics inhibit the sodium-potassium-chloride cotransporter in the thick ascending limb of the loop of Henle.","By blocking sodium reabsorption in the loop of Henle, loop diuretics disrupt the concentration gradient needed for water reabsorption.","Loop diuretics cause increased excretion of sodium, potassium, chloride, and water."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52344"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16773"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52344"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T07:40:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T07:41:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9464"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descr